title: Nintendo N64 Raspberry Pi Case
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Now printable on a 150mmx150mm bed!

I wanted a cool looking Raspberry Pi case that celebrated the good times I had playing N64 with my family and friends!

This will need support for printing, but not full support. I've used Slic3r and Cura to print this successfully.

  • With Slic3r I was able to produce support only for the vent pieces on the bottom by messing with the "Overhang threshold" option under Print Settings>Support Material. The rest of the bottom I printed as bridges and I just trimmed off the loose strands, much easier.
  • With Cura, I used 10% grid support, but you could probably get away with 5%. If you're printing in PLA have your print fan on 100% during all bridging. Controller and cord ports on the front and back don't require support.

Note - Pictures above are from a beta version, you shouldn't have to shred parts of the inside case anymore!

Things you'll need:

  • Raspberry Pi 3B

  • 5V 2.5A microUSB charger for the Pi

  • 32GB MicroSD card for Pi

  • 4 USB N64 controllers purchased from your favorite online retailer

  • HDMI cord of appropriate length

  • 30mmx30mmx7mm 5v fan for cooling

  • Couple small screws/standoffs for mounting the Pi

USB controllers can be pushed through the controller ports on the front. Will be a tight fit, but mine made it through ok. I widened the port on the back so that the HDMI can halfway sit in the port.

Find some small screws that won't protruded from the top the the case and attach so the Pi sits in comfortably.

Things to do/improve:

  • Add an embossed N64 logo to the front.

  • Make working Power/Reset buttons.

  • Shave the bottom layer off the N64 stl, the circle pieces on the bottom are just a hair bigger then the rest of the model.

For the second week in a row we got to 3D scan a live animal on set. There are challenges when scanning live objects because they move all the time. I took the camera mount from bkindler and the thumbscrew from mmiller7, put them together to make a better tripod mount. After printing just press fit (maybe glue) in a standard 1/4" nut, at which time, a standard tripod mounting block should attach without much fuss.

I have not printed this yet (planning to shortly) so I don't know if it will work 100%, but I can't see any obvious reason why it wouldn't. If I run into any issues after printing, I will fix and update the file.

------ UPDATE

So long story short if you print the mount flat the camera clips are -WAY- too weak and will break if you look at them wrong. So print these on their side and use version 2 that has added supports for the camera clips. The one that I printed came out well using Simplify 3D with 3mm supports, and made with silver ABS plastic. Much more rigid. So unless the camera falls out when I take it home, I'm calling this one done.

title: Snake - Vikings 3D Prophecy - Episode 15 - All His Angels

description.text:
This weeks 3D Prophecy item is a snake that we 3D scanned live on set in Ireland. With 3D scanning its really important for your object to be stationary. We worked with the animal handler on the Vikings show to help position the snake so it would stay still long enough for a good 3D scan. We were then able to translate all of that data we captured into a beautiful color 3D model of the snake. We then used a full color industrial 3D printing technology called color jet printing (CJP). Color jet printing works like a 2D printer where it drops ink and binder (glue) on top of a surface of powder, one layer at a time.

The challenge with the snake was to make it looks as real as possible. The 3D Scanning helped us capture the natural form it also helped us capture the color gradient on the snake. From that information we were able to create a design of a realistic snake.

A fully parametric mouthpiece for a penny whistle (or similar instrument). Much inspiration and guidance came from http://www.ggwhistles.com/howto/ Thank you Guido I am interested to hear about your experiments, what settings give the best sound. Happy experimenting

• Tweak the OpenSCAD file
  • Make a new STL
  • Print it
  • Attach tube
  • Tune it
    • To make yourself a fully functional penny whistle, first get yourself a length of tube. You probably have something lying around just waiting for this project to come up. Measure the inside and outside diameter. Put your measurements into the OpenSCAD file and print the mouthpiece. It will not make any noise until you attach it to the tube (although if you cup your hand just right you can make an annoying squeek). The STL file is for a tube with an outer diameter of 21mm, unless you have a matching tube you will need to modify the OpenSCAD and regenerate the STL. I printed this whistle standing on the mouthpiece with full supports and it worked first try. I have printed two and one came out a lot quieter than the other (I am having big print-quality issues at the moment) but they both worked. Once you are making sound you will need to trim the tube and tune your whistle. Have a look at http://www.ggwhistles.com/howto/ for some quite detailed instructions. All the parameters in the file will change the performance of the whistle in different ways, some information is included in the comments, for more detail see http://www.ggwhistles.com/howto/. Update:
    New SCAD file with a much improved lip design. It now scales well along a wider range.
    New mouthpiece, tinWhistle.stl, added for variety, much larger windway than tinWhie.stl

description.text:
2/22/17 Slight change for M3x6mm motor mounting screws.If you print the original I recommend 8mm screws. Otherwise the rev2 file works with M3x6mm .50 thread screws.

I decided to rebuild my Cheerson CX-20 in a F450 frame but I am not satisfied with the stiffness of the kit arms. I found an arm design I liked and I hacked it making them slightly shorter and they are stiffer than the F450 kit arms but I wanted better. In searching for an arm on Thingiverse I came across some motor mounts that attach to the ends of carbon fiber tubes but they are 16mm and I wanted to use 12mm tubes. So this design was born.

Keep in mind it is a work in progress. I have not yet ordered my tubes or printed these yet so they may change in the near future.

Required Parts
Carbon fiber tube 12mm OD with 8mm ID
4x M3 Bolts 25mm length
8x M3 Washers
4x M3 Nyloc Nuts

Print out of PLA at .2 layer and 50 percent infill

description.text:
On the back of my last mod, Anet A6 Frame Secure and due to the fact I use a glass plate and was getting tired of having to unclip the glass to get to the adjustment screws for the bed height, I decided to go to bottom adjustment rather than the screws on the top.

A little side note on the standard aluminum hotplate, it's not level, remove it from your printer and put a straight edge across the diagonal corners, there's a depression in the middle. So if you adjust the corners perfectly, the central area will have a much larger gap, about 0.3mm compared to the 0.1 you set at the corners. By moving to a glass bed you even this out and get a consistent gap across the whole bed.

Again there are many similar projects out there, none of which I particularly liked so I set about making my own. This is a design from scratch project, I took careful measurements of the areas that may come close to the adjusters, and tried to make the parts as big as they could possibly be. This should be ok for an A8 printer as well though you would have to check the clearances yourself as I don't have an A8.

I went for a 5 pointed star type design to allow finger space for easy adjustment, in fact, this works so nicely you can adjust with one finger while checking the gap with your other hand. When the points are set to stick out the furthest they clear all the body work by a good 1-2mm. Again the size for the nut and the hole for the screw are intentionally snug, the nut will defo not fall out. I've included a picture on how I inserted the nuts into the knob using the nuts and bolts that came off the heated bed.

You will need to drill out the threaded section of the H bracket that the bed secures to. The thread diameter is 2.8mm, I drilled it first at 3mm and found it tended to bind a little so opened that up to 3.5mm and the bed moves perfectly freely. You need to secure the original screw securely to the heated bed with a nut, make sure it's tight or when adjusting the knob the screw will spin and no adjustment will be made.

Prints fine in Cura 2.3.1 or using Cura slicer from Repetier, print speed about 55mm/s, 0.2 layer height, 20% or higher infill, i also chose 4 perimeters to give the material around the screw holes more strength

I gave both bits a decent enough sand-down before painting, a good layer of primer, a layer of brown arcrylic paint, and finally some darker browns and blacks for weathering. (Paint job's a bit dodgy as I only had a super fat brush and CBA'd to go to the shop)

title: Nerf High Speed Automatic Dart Pusher Mechanism

description.text:
This is a dart pusher mechanism for a full auto Nerf blaster. It has a lower gear ratio than the stock pusher mechanism, resulting in a higher rate of fire.

This is a modified version of a previous design created by blasterforgePH. It has been modified to improve reliability and reduce the risk of parts breaking.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Printrbot Simple Metal

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.4mm

Notes:

The internal parts were printed at 100% infill, the case was printed at 15% infill.

It is recommended to print the gears and pusher arm out of something stronger than PLA to improve durability. I used nylon for Gear A and the pusher arm.

Gear B is the only part that should require supports.

Other parts required:

-1 #6-32 screw
-4 #2-56 screws
-1 pinion gear from a Blade 180 or Xtreme Pro 180 motor
-A small amount of epoxy
-2 screws to mount the motor. I believe these are M2x4mm flat countersunk screws
-hot glue
-threadlocker or nail polish

A #6-32 screw is required to hold the main gear in place. This screw must be glued in place, as otherwise the gear will turn the screw and tighten or loosen it to the point that the mechanism will not work.

Mounting screws are required for attaching the motor.

4 screws the same size as the ones found in a Nerf blaster are required to hold the 2 halves of the case together. #2-56 screws should work.

Additionally, the new version of Gear A is designed to have a metal pinion gear, the kind from a Blade 180 or Xtreme Pro 180 motor, epoxied to the inside of it. This is to fix an issue where the gear would start to slip off the motor axle and be ruined. This was seen when using PLA to print the parts. The metal gear should be fixed to the motor axle using threadlocker or nail polish.

Demonstration

The above video shows a blaster firing 12 darts using this mechanism. It is using Xtreme Pro 180 motors.

Note that this pusher mechanism required motors with a lot of torque for the pusher motor and flywheel motors, such as Xtreme Pro 180 motors.

Rayven

This is the blaster in the demonstration video. The pusher box will work in the Rayven with holes cut in the shell.

Stryfe

This is a test fit of the mechanism without the motor. It has since been successfully used in a Stryfe.

Possible future updates

-External box to hold motor in place
-new version of Gear B to use a screw in place of the 3D printed nub on top of the gear to move the pusher arm
